XVIII. The same may be said of the evil inflicted through their property, or the like, upon individuals who have not consented to the crime, on account of the delict of the general body.

XIX. If we ask why, since the heir is bound to the other debts of the deceased, he is not bound to his punishment, as Paulus says the commentators* have decided, this is the true cause3 that the heir represents the person of the deceased, not in his deserts, which are matters merely personal, but in his possessions3 and with them are inseparably connected his debts 3 and accordingly this rule came in as soon as ownership came in. So Dio Prusaeensis.
